                <h5>HPHT Diamonds</h5>
                <p>Natural diamonds are formed deep in the earth’s crust, under high temperature and pressure conditions. These diamonds take several years to form and can only be mined when volcanic activity brings the stones closer to the earth’s surface. The HPHT process seeks to mimic the high temperature and pressure conditions that are found in the earth’s crust. To create these diamonds, a small diamond seed is placed into carbon. Then, either with the help of a belt press, a cubic press or a split-sphere press, the seed is exposed to temperatures as high as 2,000° Celsius. It is also put under immense pressure of 1.5 million pounds per square inch. Under these conditions, the pure carbon around the seed starts to melt and a diamond forms around the starter seed. Once cooled, a pure carbon diamond is formed.</p>
                    <h5>CVD Diamonds</h5>
                    <p>These diamonds start with a thin slice of a diamond seed. Often, this thin slice is taken from an HPHT diamond. This seed is placed in a sealed chamber known as a plasma reactor. The seed is then heated up to a temperature of 800° Celsius, following which the chamber is filled with carbon-rich gases like methane. Technology similar to that of lasers or microwaves is then used to ionise the gases into plasma. The ionisation process breaks down the molecular bonds of the gases, allowing pure carbon to adhere to the diamond seed and slowly crystallise.
                    </p>
